Finally, we computed the biodiversity number θ proposed by Volkov [22] through Eq. 11 using the fit parameters. Figure 4 shows how θ increases at higher similarity thresholds, pointing out that biodiversity increases at lower phylogenetic levels. Moreover, this parameter is capable to distinguish the animal species, exhibiting similar values and trends for animal of the same species and separating animal from different species. In order to compare our result with other commonly used biodiversity indexes, we computed, for all samples at the four similarity thresholds, the first and second order Hill’s numbers [37, 38] 
